":{"1376–1417":"1376–1417","1390–1420":"1390–1420","1405–Male":"1405–Deceased","1417–1490":"1417–1490","1417–Male":"1417–Deceased","1417–1489":"1417–1489","–Male":"Deceased","1330–Male":"1330–Deceased","1355–1377":"1355–1377","Aft 1377":"after 1377","1330":"1330","before 1417":"before 1417","1490":"1490","1390":"1390","1489":"1489","1377":"1377","1355":"1355","1376":"1376","1420":"1420","by 1402":"1402","1417":"1417","1405":"1405","Great Fulford, Devon, England":"Great Fulford, Devon, England, United Kingdom","Williton, Somerset, England":"Williton, Somerset, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Langdon","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of various places, for example in Devon, Dorset, Essex, Kent, and Warwickshire, so named from Old English <i>lang</i>, <i>long</i> ‘long’ + <i>dūn</i> ‘hill’. See also   Longden  .","History: Samuel Langdon, Harvard College president in 1774–80, was born in Boston, MA, in 1723 but lived out his years in Hampton Falls, NH. Three of his children left descendants. His grandfather Philip (born 1646) had came from Braunton in Devon, England, and was married in Andover, Essex County, MA, in 1684. Another early Langdon immigrant was Tobias Langdon, who came to North America before 1660 and settled in Portsmouth, NH. His great-grandson John was a revolutionary war leader, US senator, and NH governor."],"variants":[{"name":"Longden","meanings":["English: habitational name, perhaps from Longendale in Derbyshire. The placename must originally have been Old English <i>lang</i> ‘long’ + <i>denu</i> ‘valley’, to which Old English <i>dæl</i> ‘dale, valley’ was tautologically added. The surname <i>Longden</i> would then represent either the original placename or a shortened form of the longer one."]},{"name":"Landon","meanings":["English: altered form of   Langdon  .","English: habitational name from Lavendon (Buckinghamshire), which is recorded as <i>Laundone</i> in 1232 and <i>Lavenden alias Launden</i> in 1639. The placename derives from the Old English personal name <i>Lāfa</i> (genitive <i>Lāfan</i>) + Old English <i>denu</i> ‘valley’.","French: from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Lando</i>, a short form of compound names based on the element <i>land</i> ‘land, territory’, via the oblique case, <i>Landonis</i>."]}]},{"name":"Wilhelma","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["from <i>wil</i> ‘will’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet’; an ancient royal name.  See also  <b>William</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"William","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Wilhelma Langdon was born in 1376, in Williton, Somerset, England, United Kingdom, her father, John de Langdon, was 47 and her mother, Joanna FitzUrse, was 21. She married Henry Fulford II in 1402. They were the parents of at least 3 sons and 2 daughters. She died in 1417, in Great Fulford, Devon, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 41."},"et":{"1376–1417":"1376–1417","1390–1420":"1390–1420","1405–Male":"1405–Surnud","1417–1490":"1417–1490","1417–Male":"1417–Surnud","1417–1489":"1417–1489","–Male":"Surnud","1330–Male":"1330–Surnud","1355–1377":"1355–1377","Aft 1377":"pärast 1377","1330":"1330","before 1417":"enne 1417","1490":"1490","1390":"1390","1489":"14